<DocLayout
  title="Documentation"
  eyebrow="Docs"
  description="The reference surface for OpenPress: what the framework is for, the API it exposes, and the boundaries between source, framework, and generated output."
>
  <h2>What you'll find here</h2>

  <p>
    OpenPress is an AI-first framework for maintainable fixed-layout documents — long-form reports, papers,
    slides, and social cards generated from a single React + MDX source tree. These docs lock down two
    questions: <em>where does OpenPress fit in your workflow</em>, and <em>which APIs are safe to depend on</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>Pages in this section</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="/docs/product-boundary"><strong>Product boundary</strong></a> — what lives in OpenPress, what
      explicitly doesn't, and which tool to reach for instead. Read this before deciding to adopt the framework.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/docs/public-api"><strong>Public API</strong></a> — the exact module exports, config schema, CSS
      variables, comment markers, and dev endpoints that are stable for 1.0. Anything outside this list is
      considered internal and may change between minor releases.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Quick links</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/quan0715/open-press">Source — github.com/quan0715/open-press</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@open-press/cli">CLI — @open-press/cli on npm</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@open-press/core">Core runtime — @open-press/core on npm</a></li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>1.0 is close.</strong> These docs reflect the surface we plan to freeze. If something in the
    repo doesn't appear here, treat it as internal — it may move or rename in a patch release.
  </div>
</DocLayout>
